{"text": " An asteroid might hit the moon, and we might have to nuke it before it does. I'm serious. So earlier this year, we thought that this asteroid might hit Earth. Good news. It won't. Bad news. It might now hit the moon. Which is very bad news, because this asteroid is the size of a 15 story building. An estimate say that an impact with the moon could cause a big cloud of debris around Earth. So NASA just came out with a real proposal for what we could do if a lunar impact becomes more likely. Option one. We could smash a spacecraft into it, hoping to nudge it off its course. The problem is we only have seven years, and for this to work, the nudge has to be done far enough in advance that it misses the moon. And you really don't want to nudge it into Earth. So NASA says that deflecting this one seems impractical. Option two. We blow it apart. They call this robust disruption. We don't exactly know how big or how dense this asteroid is. So based on our estimates, NASA suggests that we use a one megaton bomb. And that looks like a very serious best option right now. The next time we'll see this asteroid will be in February with James Webb's Space Telescope. And that'll refine our estimate, but not confirm it. But in 2028, when we get a better look with our Earth-based telescopes, then we'll decide what to do. If you want to know how we defend Earth from asteroids, go watch our video with Mark Rober.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 4.72, "text": " An asteroid might hit the moon, and we might have to nuke it before it does.", "tokens": [50364, 1107, 33833, 1062, 2045, 264, 7135, 11, 293, 321, 1062, 362, 281, 3822, 330, 309, 949, 309, 775, 13, 50600], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15412974887424044, "compression_ratio": 1.7272727272727273, "no_speech_prob": 0.0011417740024626255}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 4.72, "end": 5.76, "text": " I'm serious.", "tokens": [50600, 286, 478, 3156, 13, 50652], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob"